cs.NI, cs.CR, cs.DS, cs.IT, cs.SI 

This paper proposes a next-generation Internet routing protocol that provides strong anonymity against an active attacker located at any single point within the network, including the user's ISP. Therefore, the most likely arXiv CS sub-category for this paper is cs.NI (Networking and Internet Architecture). The paper also discusses security and privacy issues, which makes cs.CR (Cryptography and Security) another likely sub-category. The paper proposes a routing protocol, which involves path construction and joining of path segments, indicating that cs.DS (Distributed, Parallel, and Cluster Computing) could also be a relevant sub-category. The paper also discusses the measurement of topological anonymity, which suggests that cs.IT (Information Theory) could be another relevant sub-category. Finally, the paper uses simulation to demonstrate the privacy and efficiency of the proposed protocol, which could also make cs.SI (Social and Information Networks) a relevant sub-category.
